revision.text:
'''Sanki Daigongen''' (三鬼大権現) is a {{ill|demon deity|ja|鬼神|12=draft|12=draft}} revered in {{ill|Tengu|ja|天狗|12=draft|12=draft}} worship and {{ill|mountain Buddhism|ja|山岳仏教|12=draft|12=draft}}, particularly within the {{ill|Shingon Buddhism|ja|真言宗|12=draft|12=draft}} tradition. It is also known as '''Itsukushima Sanki-bō''' (厳島三鬼坊).

== Overview ==
Sanki Daigongen is primarily enshrined at the {{ill|Sanki-dō|ja|三鬼堂|12=draft|12=draft}} on {{ill|Mount Misen|ja|弥山 (広島県)|12=draft|12=draft}} and within the {{ill|Maniden|ja|魔尼殿|12=draft|12=draft}} at {{ill|Daishō-in|ja|大聖院 (宮島)|12=draft|12=draft}} on {{ill|Miyajima|ja|宮島|12=draft|12=draft}}, located in {{ill|Hatsukaichi|ja|廿日市市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hiroshima Prefecture|ja|広島県|12=draft|12=draft}}. Sanki Daigongen is believed to command both great and small Tengu as retainers, using vast supernatural powers to save sentient beings. Locally, it is affectionately referred to as '''Sanki-san'''. It is said that {{ill|Itō Hirobumi|ja|伊藤博文|12=draft|12=draft}}, Japan’s first Prime Minister, was a devout follower.

The three deities of Sanki Daigongen are:
* '''Tsuichō Kishin (追帳鬼神)''': A deity governing the virtue of "fortune and virtue" (福徳), with {{ill|Dainichi Nyorai|ja|大日如来|12=draft|12=draft}} as the {{ill|honji-butsu|ja|本地仏|12=draft|12=draft}} (original Buddha).
* '''Jibi Kishin (時眉鬼神)''': A deity overseeing the virtue of "wisdom" (知恵), with {{ill|Kokūzō Bosatsu|ja|虚空蔵菩薩|12=draft|12=draft}} as the honji-butsu. Kokūzō Bosatsu is also the principal deity enshrined at {{ill|Misen Main Hall|ja|弥山本堂|12=draft|12=draft}}.
* '''Mara Kishin (魔羅鬼神)''': A deity associated with the virtue of "subjugation" (降伏), with {{ill|Fudō Myōō|ja|不動明王|12=draft|12=draft}} as the honji-butsu.

Following the {{ill|Shinbutsu Bunri|ja|神仏分離令|12=draft|12=draft}} (the separation of Shinto and Buddhism), the deities were relocated from the original {{ill|Miyama Shrine|ja|御山神社|12=draft|12=draft}} to the current Sanki-dō.

=== Origin ===
It is believed that the revered monk {{ill|Kūkai|ja|空海|12=draft|12=draft}} (also known as Kōbō Daishi) enshrined Sanki Daigongen in 806 CE (Daido 1) when he founded Mount Misen as a sacred site.

=== Mantra ===
The mantra associated with Sanki Daigongen is:
* '''On Aratan Nō Un Sowaka''' (オン・アラタンノウ・ウン・ソワカ).

Additionally, there are {{ill|wasan|ja|和讃|12=draft|12=draft}} (Buddhist hymns) praising the virtues of Sanki Daigongen.
== See Also ==
* {{ill|List of Buddhas|ja|仏の一覧|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Gongen|ja|権現|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Daitengu|ja|大天狗|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Mountain worship|ja|山岳信仰|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Mitaki-dera|ja|三瀧寺|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Guhin|ja|狗賓|12=draft|12=draft}}

