== Overview == Sanki Daigongen is primarily enshrined at the {{ill|Sanki-dō|ja|三鬼堂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sanki-dō|qq=}} on [[:en:Mount Misen|Mount Misen]] and within the {{ill|Maniden|ja|魔尼殿|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Maniden|qq=}} at [[:en:Daishō-in|Daishō-in]] on [[:en:Miyajima|Miyajima]], located in [[:en:Hatsukaichi|Hatsukaichi]], [[:en:Hiroshima Prefecture|Hiroshima Prefecture]]. Sanki Daigongen is believed to command both great and small Tengu as retainers, using vast supernatural powers to save sentient beings. Locally, it is affectionately referred to as '''Sanki-san'''. It is said that [[:en:Itō Hirobumi|Itō Hirobumi]], Japan’s first Prime Minister, was a devout follower.
The three deities of Sanki Daigongen are: * '''Tsuichō Kishin (追帳鬼神)''': A deity governing the virtue of "fortune and virtue" (福徳), with [[:en:Vairocana|Dainichi Nyorai]] as the {{ill|honji-butsu|ja|本地仏|1=Honji_suijaku#Honji Buddha|lt=Honji Buddha|2=ja|3=本地垂迹|4=fr|5=Honji suijaku|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/honji-butsu|13=User:Immanuelle/Honji_suijaku#Honji Buddha|qq=}} (original Buddha). * '''Jibi Kishin (時眉鬼神)''': A deity overseeing the virtue of "wisdom" (知恵), with [[:en:Ākāśagarbha|Kokūzō Bosatsu]] as the honji-butsu. Kokūzō Bosatsu is also the principal deity enshrined at {{ill|Misen Main Hall|ja|弥山本堂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Misen Main Hall|qq=}}. * '''Mara Kishin (魔羅鬼神)''': A deity associated with the virtue of "subjugation" (降伏), with [[:en:Acala|Fudō Myōō]] as the honji-butsu.
Following the {{ill|Shinbutsu Bunri|ja|神仏分離令|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu Bunri|qq=}} (the separation of Shinto and Buddhism), the deities were relocated from the original {{ill|Miyama Shrine|ja|御山神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyama Shrine|qq=}} to the current Sanki-dō.
=== Origin === It is believed that the revered monk [[:en:Kūkai|Kūkai]] (also known as Kōbō Daishi) enshrined Sanki Daigongen in 806 CE (Daido 1) when he founded Mount Misen as a sacred site.
=== Mantra === The mantra associated with Sanki Daigongen is: * '''On Aratan Nō Un Sowaka''' (オン・アラタンノウ・ウン・ソワカ).
Additionally, there are [[:en:Wasan|wasan]] (Buddhist hymns) praising the virtues of Sanki Daigongen. == See Also == * {{ill|List of Buddhas|ja|仏の一覧|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/List of Buddhas|qq=}} * [[:en:Gongen|Gongen]] * {{ill|Daitengu|ja|大天狗|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daitengu|qq=}} * [[:en:Mountain worship|Mountain worship]] * [[:en:Mitaki-dera|Mitaki-dera]] * {{ill|Guhin|ja|狗賓|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Guhin|qq=}}
